Data set: Identifiable collection of data. A Data set is a structures collection of (digital) information which describes certain common properties of entities using an agreed set of attributes and standards

The Thematic Logical Model TLM (Logical) Model. This is the model that describes: - the concepts and relationships in the domain that are to be represented in the suite of information products - how the information products are related and remain coherent Describes the domain model from an information system perspective. For FSDF we will be using the ISO profile of UML (ISO 19103 + ISO19109) (need link) and use elements of the ISO 19100 Harmonized Model This is necessary to ensure that the suite of products within the theme will fit together. The difference between this model and the Business Model is not always clear. However a good rule of thumb is that if you find yourself discussing types (strings, ints, etc) in the Business Model you've slipped into Logical Modelling. This model is the lowest common denominator that is able to encompass existing models (Modeling. stakeholder models). It is developed from existing implementation models and then tested against the Business Model to ensure it reflects the concepts there.

ANZLIC will continue to provide the broad policy direction and oversight of the FSDF. ANZLIC remains in a unique position within the Australian spatial community to align the direction of users, custodians and suppliers of foundation spatial data. ANZLIC, through its secretariat and contact officers, will remain closely engaged with Theme Sponsors and Custodians to assist in the planning and reporting on the evolution of datasets against long-term goals.
Direct and provide oversight of FSDF

This committee will be responsible for the day-to-day management of the FSDF. Membership will comprise senior representatives from the Department of Communications and Geoscience Australia and this committee will meet monthly.

These groups will be responsible for the development / evolution of the datasets within their respective themes against their three-year plan and annual vision statements. Each group will led by their theme sponsor and will comprise the custodians, aggregators, users and suppliers. These groups will replace the existing thematic working groups.

This committee will be responsible for industry engagement; and will comprise industry bodies, jurisdictional representatives, eminent individuals from the spatial community and the Project Management Committee.

This group will be responsible for providing technical advice to the FSDF Project Management Committee and the theme leadership groups as required. This group will comprise the Australian Government representatives to the Open Geospatial Consortium, the international technical committee for geospatial standards (ISO/TC211) and Standards Australia; as well as representatives from research organisations such as NICTA, CSIRO and the Cooperative Research Centre for Spatial Information (CRCSI).

Key FSDF Supplier: A key FSDF supplier is a critical supplier of data to a National Foundation Data set. A key FSDF supplier may be from the Commonwealth, a Jurisdiction or local government or the private sector and would be identified for their key role by a sponsor or custodian. A FSDF supplier may apply for membership to a working group or be invited by the Theme Sponsor or Data set custodian. Contribution Expected: Participation in working groups

Key FSDF User: A key FSDF user is a consumer of a National Foundation Data set as an input to solve problems and /or make decisions. A key FSDF user may be from the Commonwealth, a Jurisdiction or the private sector and would be identified for their key role by a sponsor or custodian. A FSDF user may apply for membership to a working group or be invited by the Theme Sponsor or Data set custodian. Contribution Expected: Participation in working groups

National Data set Aggregator for the FSDF: An agency or organisation that aggregates a National Foundation Data set from component data sets. This agency or organisation may either be the custodian or a third party aggregator who performs the role under contract or agreement. A National Data set Aggregator would receive acknowledgement of their position and guidance on their role by the chair of ANZLIC The Spatial Information Council on behalf of the council and the National Data set Custodian. Contribution Expected: Participation in working groups

An agency or organisation (Australian, state or territory) having a special interest in ensuring that the National Foundation Datasets within a particular theme are widely available and of high quality. The Sponsor's role will include liaising with other national sponsors, consulting a community of users and coordinating activities with custodians to report on the progress of the foundation datasets in line with the broader ANZLIC objectives. The Sponsor will update ANZLIC on progress of the FSDF at its regular meetings, held three times each year. .

An agency or organisation identified as being responsible for the development and management of a national foundation Data set, and who has the right to determine the condition applying to the use, distribution and composition of the national foundation Data set. The national Data set custodian would be responsible for the ongoing evolution of datasets as defined by itself and the theme leadership groups. Their role would comprise the development and delivery of their national foundation Data set and the maintenance of a close working relationship with thematic sponsors to ensure that yearly vision statements are achieved.
